---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} />
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<h1>🚀 The Firecracker MicroVM Series</h1>
			<p>
				Welcome to my engineering blog! Here I detail the process of building a lightning-fast
				MicroVM orchestrator from scratch using Rust, Firecracker, and WebSockets.
			</p>
			<p>
				The goal of this project was to explore hardware isolation, dynamic Linux networking, and the hidden complexities of terminal emulation bridging. Dive into the 3-part series:
			</p>
			<ul>
				<li>
					<strong><a href="/my-coding-blog/blog/part-1-orchestrator/">Part 1: The Orchestrator</a></strong> - Spawning Firecracker, managing Unix sockets, and the ephemeral "Clone-on-Demand" storage pattern.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong><a href="/my-coding-blog/blog/part-2-network-handoff/">Part 2: The Network Handoff</a></strong> - Tap devices, /24 subnets, NAT routing, and solving the Resource Busy error.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong><a href="/my-coding-blog/blog/part-3-guest-experience/">Part 3: The Guest Experience</a></strong> - Building the guest-agent in Rust, VSOCK communication, and dynamic terminal resizing via ioctl.
				</li>
			</ul>
			<p>
				Head over to the <a href="/my-coding-blog/blog/">Blog</a> for all posts.
			</p>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
